          "text": "Base directory for this skill: /home/leon0399/.claude/skills/octocat\n\n# GitHub Skill\n\nUse the `gh` CLI for all GitHub interactions. Never suggest the web UI when `gh` can do it.\n\n## Pull Requests\n\nCreate a PR with a multi-line body (the `--body` flag mangles `\\n` into literal characters — always use `--body-file`):\n\n```bash\ncat > /tmp/pr-body.md << 'EOF'\n## Summary\nDescription here.\nEOF\ngh pr create --base main --head <branch> --title \"<title>\" --body-file /tmp/pr-body.md\n```\n\nIf you must use inline text, use shell ANSI-C quoting: `--body $'line1\\n\\nline2'`\n\nCheck CI status:\n```bash\ngh pr checks <number>\n```\n\nView a PR with specific fields:\n```bash\ngh pr view <number> --json title,state,reviews,statusCheckRollup\n```\n\nCheckout a PR locally:\n```bash\ngh pr checkout 123\n```\n\nView PR diff:\n```bash\ngh pr diff 123\ngh pr diff 123 --name-only  # file list only\n```\n\nMerge a PR:\n```bash\ngh pr merge 123 --squash --delete-branch   # squash merge + cleanup\ngh pr merge 123 --rebase --delete-branch   # rebase merge + cleanup\n```\n\nEdit PR metadata:\n```bash\ngh pr edit 123 --title \"New title\" --add-label bug --add-reviewer user1\n```\n\n## CI / GitHub Actions\n\nList recent workflow runs:\n```bash\ngh run list --limit 10\n```\n\nView a failed run and its logs:\n```bash\ngh run view <run-id>\ngh run view <run-id> --log-failed\n```\n\nWatch a run until it completes (use `--exit-status` to get non-zero exit on failure):\n```bash\ngh run watch <run-id> --exit-status\n```\n\n## PR Reviews\n\n### Fetching review threads\n\nUse the bundled `pr-reviews` skill/script for fetching review threads — it handles GraphQL pagination and flattens the response. If `pr-reviews` is unavailable, use the GraphQL query below.\n\nThe REST API (`/pulls/{number}/comments`) does **not** expose `isResolved` — you need GraphQL for resolution status. This is why models often get review fetching wrong: they try REST and miss critical fields.\n\n```bash\n# Preferred: use the pr-reviews script\n~/.claude/skills/pr-reviews/SKILL.sh owner/repo 123\n\n# Fallback: REST API (no resolution status, no thread grouping)\ngh api repos/OWNER/REPO/pulls/123/comments --paginate \\\n  --jq '.[] | {id, path, line, body, user: .user.login, created_at}'\n```\n\n### Fetching review verdicts (approve/request changes)\n\n```bash\n# List all review verdicts\ngh pr view 123 -R owner/repo --json reviews \\\n  --jq '.reviews[] | {author: .author.login, state: .state, submittedAt: .submittedAt}'\n\n# Or via REST\ngh api repos/OWNER/REPO/pulls/123/reviews \\\n  --jq '.[] | {id, state, user: .user.login, submitted_at}'\n```\n\n### Submitting a review\n\n```bash\n# Approve\ngh pr review 123 -R owner/repo --approve\n\n# Request changes with comment\ngh pr review 123 -R owner/repo --request-changes --body \"Please fix the null check\"\n\n# Leave a general review comment (not approve/reject)\ngh pr review 123 -R owner/repo --comment --body \"Looks good overall, minor nits\"\n```\n\nFor multi-line review bodies, use `--body-file` (same as PR creation — `--body` mangles newlines):\n```bash\ncat > /tmp/review.md << 'EOF'\nReviewed the auth changes. Two concerns:\n1. Token expiry not handled\n2. Missing rate limit check\nEOF\ngh pr review 123 -R owner/repo --request-changes --body-file /tmp/review.md\n```\n\n### Replying to a review comment\n\nThe reply endpoint requires BOTH the PR number AND the comment ID in the path. This is a common mistake — omitting the PR number gives a 404:\n\n```\nWRONG: repos/OWNER/REPO/pulls/comments/COMMENT_ID/replies        (404!)\nRIGHT: repos/OWNER/REPO/pulls/PR_NUMBER/comments/COMMENT_ID/replies\n```\n\n```bash\n# Reply to a review comment (PR_NUMBER and COMMENT_ID are both required)\ngh api repos/OWNER/REPO/pulls/PR_NUMBER/comments/COMMENT_ID/replies \\\n  -f body=\"Fixed in the latest commit\"\n```\n\nTo find the comment ID to reply to:\n```bash\ngh api repos/OWNER/REPO/pulls/PR_NUMBER/comments --paginate \\\n  --jq '.[] | {id, path, line, author: .user.login, body: .body[:80]}'\n```\n\n### Resolving a review thread\n\nResolution requires GraphQL — there is no REST endpoint. You need the thread's GraphQL node ID (the `PRRT_...` ID from the `pr-reviews` script or from the GraphQL reviewThreads query):\n\n```bash\ngh api graphql -f query='\nmutation($threadId: ID!) {\n  resolveReviewThread(input: {threadId: $threadId}) {\n    thread { isResolved }\n  }\n}' -f threadId=\"PRRT_kwDOxxxxxx\"\n```\n\nTo unresolve:\n```bash\ngh api graphql -f query='\nmutation($threadId: ID!) {\n  unresolveReviewThread(input: {threadId: $threadId}) {\n    thread { isResolved }\n  }\n}' -f threadId=\"PRRT_kwDOxxxxxx\"\n```\n\n### Commenting on a PR (top-level, not inline review)\n\nTop-level PR comments use the issues API (PRs are issues in GitHub's model):\n\n```bash\n# Add a comment\ngh pr comment 123 -R owner/repo --body \"Thanks for the review, all addressed\"\n\n# Or with body-file for multi-line\ngh pr comment 123 -R owner/repo --body-file /tmp/comment.md\n```\n\n## Issue Relationships (Sub-issues, Parent/Child)\n\nThe `gh issue` CLI does not natively support sub-issues or parent relationships. Use `gh api` with the REST endpoints directly. These endpoints require the `2026-03-10` API version header.\n\n### Key gotcha: issue `id` vs `number`\n\nThe sub-issues API takes `sub_issue_id` which is the **internal numeric ID**, not the issue number. `gh issue view --json id` returns the GraphQL `node_id` (wrong). Get the correct integer ID with:\n\n```bash\ngh api repos/OWNER/REPO/issues/42 --jq '.id'\n```\n\n### Add a sub-issue (parent/child relationship)\n\nThere is no \"set parent\" API — you can only add a child to a parent. To set a parent for an issue, call `addSubIssue` on the parent with the child's ID. Both REST and GraphQL work:\n\n```bash\n# REST: add child to parent (uses internal integer ID)\nCHILD_ID=$(gh api repos/OWNER/REPO/issues/CHILD_NUMBER --jq '.id')\ngh api repos/OWNER/REPO/issues/PARENT_NUMBER/sub_issues \\\n  -X POST -F \"sub_issue_id=$CHILD_ID\"\n\n# GraphQL: add child to parent (uses node_id)\ngh api graphql -f query='\nmutation($parentId: ID!, $childId: ID!) {\n  addSubIssue(input: {issueId: $parentId, subIssueId: $childId}) {\n    issue { number title }\n    subIssue { number title }\n  }\n}' -f parentId=\"$(gh api repos/OWNER/REPO/issues/PARENT --jq '.node_id')\" \\\n   -f childId=\"$(gh api repos/OWNER/REPO/issues/CHILD --jq '.node_id')\"\n```\n\n### List sub-issues\n\n```bash\ngh api repos/OWNER/REPO/issues/PARENT_NUMBER/sub_issues \\\n  --jq '.[] | {number, title, state}'\n```\n\n### Get parent of an issue\n\n```bash\ngh api repos/OWNER/REPO/issues/CHILD_NUMBER/parent --jq '{number, title}'\n```\n\n### Remove a sub-issue\n\n```bash\nCHILD_ID=$(gh api repos/OWNER/REPO/issues/CHILD_NUMBER --jq '.id')\ngh api repos/OWNER/REPO/issues/PARENT_NUMBER/sub_issue \\\n  -X DELETE -F \"sub_issue_id=$CHILD_ID\"\n```\n\n### Blocked / blocked-by (issue dependencies)\n\nSame `id` gotcha as sub-issues — the API takes the internal integer ID, not the issue number.\n\n```bash\n# Mark issue 43 as blocked by issue 42\nBLOCKER_ID=$(gh api repos/OWNER/REPO/issues/42 --jq '.id')\ngh api repos/OWNER/REPO/issues/43/dependencies/blocked_by \\\n  -X POST -F \"issue_id=$BLOCKER_ID\"\n\n# List what's blocking issue 43\ngh api repos/OWNER/REPO/issues/43/dependencies/blocked_by \\\n  --jq '.[] | {number, title, state}'\n\n# List what issue 42 is blocking\ngh api repos/OWNER/REPO/issues/42/dependencies/blocking \\\n  --jq '.[] | {number, title, state}'\n\n# Remove the dependency\nBLOCKER_ID=$(gh api repos/OWNER/REPO/issues/42 --jq '.id')\ngh api repos/OWNER/REPO/issues/43/dependencies/blocked_by/$BLOCKER_ID -X DELETE\n```\n\n## Search\n\n```bash\ngh search code \"pattern\" --repo owner/repo        # search code in a repo\ngh search issues \"label:bug state:open\"            # search issues\ngh search prs \"is:open review:required\"            # search PRs\ngh search repos \"stars:>1000 language:rust\"        # search repos\n```\n\n## API for Advanced Queries\n\nUse `gh api` when subcommands don't expose what you need:\n\n```bash\ngh api repos/OWNER/REPO/pulls/55 --jq '.title, .state, .user.login'\n```\n\nMost commands support `--json` + `--jq` for structured output:\n```bash\ngh issue list --json number,title --jq '.[] | \"\\(.number): \\(.title)\"'\n```\n\n## Commit Signing\n\n- Never alter `user.signingkey` or signing mode in git config.\n- If signing is already configured, use it as-is.\n- If not configured, proceed without signing — do not set it up.\n\n## Pre-commit Hooks\n\nWhen a hook fails, fix the underlying issue directly rather than bypassing with `--no-verify`. For TypeScript linting issues, delegate to the typescript-magician skill if available.\n\n## Rules\n\n- Validate unfamiliar `gh` subcommands with `gh help <command>` before using them.\n- After opening a PR, watch CI with `gh run watch <run-id> --exit-status` and proactively fix failures.\n\n\nARGUMENTS: Create a pull request for the current branch feat/providers-models-config against master",
